Editor						December 12, 1991
Computer News 80
P. O. Box 680
Casper, Wyoming	82602-0680

Dear Sir or Madam,

Thank you for mentioning M. A. D. Software in your December (Vol 4, No 12)
issue on Page 2.   However, the information you received about our demise
was incorrect and/or misleading and we hope to clarify this in this letter.

In a recent flyer, we announced that M. A. D. Software would cease to
purchase Radio Shack PALs and ROMs, and stop the production some of our
own ROMs next year.

We have been obtaining pre-programmed PALs and ROMs in quantity from Radio
Shack, but the demand has dwindled to the point that it no longer makes sense
to carry them.  In fact, some of the parts are no longer available from Radio
Shack, and our current stock is all that remains.  We will cease trying to
obtain additional components from Radio Shack on March 1st, but will continue
to offer our remaining stock until our supply is exhausted.

Similarly, certain versions of our XROM, XDROM, 4P-ROM are to be discontinued.
We will cease production of these EPROMS in April 1992.  The versions affected
are for Powersoft Series I hard disk drivers.   We will also stop making
customized 4P-ROMs. 

Our other products will remain available for now and we have some new products
we plan to release in the new year.

We would be interested in you putting a question to your readership.  Some
years ago, one of our programmers wrote a LS-DOS 6 networking system that
utilized the Radio Shack Network 4 hardware.  M. A. D. Software didn't feel
that there was sufficient interest in this sort of product since someone
would have to own at least two Model 4 systems.  They would also have to have
Network 4 hardware, something that we assume few people have, and is probably
difficult to get.  We get a request for this from time to time, and we really
can't get excited about putting a significant amount of work into a product
that few people would use.  

So the question is, do your readers have systems that are equipped with
Network 4 support?  (A machine has Network 4 support if there is a small block
of switches next to where the power cable connects to the Model 4/4D.) 
Many schools had these systems and have probably sold them off by now, so it
is possible that individuals have them now.  Also, do any of the Radio Shack
equipment retailers have any significant quantity of the network boards?
(They are not available from any division of Radio Shack.)  And finally, if
you had the hardware or could get it cheaply, would you be interested in
sharing a hard disk and other resources between multiple computers?  If the
answers are sent to us, we will be happy to report back with a tally of
responses.

On another subject, please send us information regarding advertising costs
for CN80, requirements, copy formats and deadlines.  Please indicate if you
accept oversize originals or if artwork has to be pre-sized.
^L
