Finally, we wanted to mention two corrections to the Q & A on Page 14.

Q:	If a 3-1/2" diskette has a hard plastic shell protecting them,
	why are they still referred to as a floppy disk and floppy disk
	drives?

The actual answer is that the term "floppy disk" and "hard disk" has always
referred to the media itself, with a "floppy" or flexible media using mylar
or a similar material as its base, and a "hard disk" using aluminum or some
other rigid material as its base.   A Bernoulli box cartridge is also in a
rigid plastic shell, but the media is flexible, so it is considered to be
a floppy disk drive.

Q:	"How many disk drives will my computer support?"

If the machine is a Model 4, 4D, II, 12, 16, or 6000 the standard Radio Shack
configuration can support up to four floppy drives and four hard disk drives.
Radio Shack offered four 15 Meg drives as the largest supported Model 4/4D
combination at one point.  (Granted, you could not have all that space online
at the same time under LDOS/TRSDOS 6/LS-DOS 6.)  If the machine is a 4P, the
standard Radio Shack configuration can support up to two floppy drives and
four hard disk drives.

All external versions of the Radio Shack hard disk controller supported up
to four hard disk drives at once.  The internal card for the 16B HD/6000 HD
allowed only two hard disk drives.


Thank you for your time, and we hope that this letter has cleared things up.


						Sincerely,



